s, newspapers, films, and more to document how the politics of visibility framed discussions around enslavement and abolition during the nineteenth and twentieth centuries. In this way, Baghoolizadeh makes visible the people and histories that were erased from Iran and its diaspora.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aBlack peoplezIranxSocial conditionsy19th century2DLC. 0aBlack peoplezIranxSocial conditionsy19th century. 0aBlack peoplezIranxSocial conditionsy20th century2DLC. 0aBlack peoplezIranxSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aRacism against Black peoplezIranxHistoryy19th century2DLC. 0aRacism against Black peoplezIranxHistoryy19th century. 0aRacism against Black peoplezIranxHistoryy20th century2DLC. 0aRacism against Black peoplezIranxHistoryy20th century. 0aSlaveryzIranxHistoryy19th century2DLC. 0aSlaveryzIranxHistoryy19th century. 0aSlaveryzIranxHistoryy20th century2DLC. 0aSlaveryzIranxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Middle Eastern Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311135689140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478059257?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478059257423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478059257/original  a978-3-11-135689-1  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles